docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:8:- `POST /api/v1/auth/login/`, `/refresh/`, `/logout/` with refresh rotation, replay rejection, revocation, auth audit events. Contracts in `docs/working/API_CONTRACTS.md`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:9:- JWT signing now uses PyJWT HS256 with `SECRET_KEY` read from `SFPCL_SECRET_KEY` and local-dev fallback. Refresh-session storage, rotation, replay rejection, and logout revocation behaviour were preserved.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:14:- A-005 resolved for backend via `PROTOTYPE_PERMISSION_ALIASES` (`export`/`export_reports`→`reports.export`, `view_loans`→`finance.loan_account.read`). Frontend union re-wiring deferred to 002D/002E.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:19:- Auth behavior moved behind explicit module functions in `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/`: `tokens.py` (encode/decode/hash/claims + `TokenError`) and `auth_service.py` (`authenticate_user`/`CredentialError`, `issue_login_tokens_and_session`, `validate_refresh_session`, `rotate_refresh_token`, `revoke_session_for_logout`, `validate_access_token`, `record_auth_event`, `auth_payload`). Views are now thin (parse → call module → translate errors). `views.py` re-exports `TokenError` and `decode_token` for backward-compatible imports.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:20:- All 002B/002B2 behavior preserved (verified by unchanged `test_auth_api.py` + new `test_auth_module.py`): PyJWT HS256, lifetimes, claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, audit events.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:24:- Current-user reads use `auth_service.current_user_payload_for_access_token()`, which calls the new session-bound `validate_access_session()`: access token must be signed, unexpired, type `access`, bound to an active `UserSession`, and owned by a user whose status can authenticate.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:25:- A-008 resolved for `/auth/me/`: logged-out/revoked sessions and suspended/inactive users cannot retrieve profile, permission, or action data. `validate_access_token()` remains the low-level stateless JWT decode helper.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:28:- Auth errors use the shared envelope: missing bearer token `401 AUTH_REQUIRED`; expired access token `401 TOKEN_EXPIRED`; refresh/wrong-type, malformed, revoked-session, inactive-user, or unknown-session tokens `401 INVALID_TOKEN`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:29:- Tests added in `test_auth_api.py` and `test_auth_module.py`: success envelope/meta, missing token, expired token, refresh misuse, inactive user, revoked session, permission sorting/empty cases, available actions, and thin-view service-boundary guardrail.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:36:- Security behavior from 002D is unchanged: session-bound bearer access validation, active-user enforcement, standard envelopes, and the existing `AUTH_REQUIRED`, `TOKEN_EXPIRED`, and `INVALID_TOKEN` cases remain covered by tests.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:44:- 002E should replace the staff demo auth shell with backend login → `/auth/me/` → protected shell state using the 002D3 data shape. Preserve the existing visual system exactly, keep borrower portal demo auth out of scope, display role/team names from `roles`/`teams`, keep `role_codes`/`team_codes` as compatibility data, and derive staff navigation/route visibility from backend canonical permissions through a documented mapping layer. Unknown permission mappings must go to `ASSUMPTIONS.md`, not invented grants.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:51:- 002EX now explicitly depends on 002E and 002D2: its tracer screen must run through authenticated staff session state, use real APIs and persistent dev SQLite for manual smoke evidence, keep automated tests on the migrated Django test database, and include an unauthenticated `401` envelope regression for at least one tracer endpoint.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:54:  - 002E maps unknown backend roles to prototype `auditor` in `mapBackendUserToFrontendUser()`. Because `Dashboard`, `MyProfile`, and other shell pages still branch on `currentUser.role`, backend roles such as `it_head` or `management_viewer` can inherit auditor-shaped dashboard/profile content even with empty permissions. Corrective slice `002E2` must replace this with a neutral/no-affordance path and test zero-permission/unmapped roles.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:56:- Source extracts for the 2026-07-03_224536 review: `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §11.4 defines `/auth/me/` profile + roles + teams + permissions; its closing implementation rule says React uses `available_actions` for UX while Django remains authoritative. `docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md` §10.6 says UI navigation must be role-aware and backend rejects unauthorized API calls. `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §13.1 includes role codes `it_head`, `internal_auditor`, `management_viewer`, and others that the frontend bridge must handle explicitly or neutrally.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:57:- 002EX must consume the 002E/002E2 bridge: no tracer screen before backend login and `/auth/me/`; no demo-auth bypass for smoke evidence; empty-permission or unmapped-role sessions must not see tracer actions or inherited auditor/admin/borrower affordances.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:58:- 002EY should make Playwright prove the same production/default auth path. Its login flow must hit the dev Django server and should include negative browser checks that missing/revoked sessions land on staff login and zero-permission/unmapped backend roles cannot expose tracer routes/actions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:59:- 002E2 completed the frontend role bridge hardening: unmapped backend roles and zero-permission seeded roles such as `it_head` and `management_viewer` now map to neutral frontend role `backend_staff`, preserve backend `roleName`/`roleCodes`/team display, and receive no prototype permissions unless canonical backend permissions map explicitly. Dashboard/profile/header branches no longer grant auditor/admin/borrower affordances to this neutral role; the header Settings shortcut is hidden unless `view_settings` is granted.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:60:- 002EX completed the first real integration proof: minimal `tracer` Django app, one migration, session-bound `/api/v1/tracer/...` endpoints, service-layer transition guards, one audit log and one workflow event per transition, a staff-shell Tracer screen, and a narrow `tracer.lifecycle.run` permission bridge. Source extracts used: `api-contracts.md` §3 requires backend-enforced workflow, explicit action endpoints, auditability, versioned `/api/v1/`, and standard envelopes; `data-model.md` §26.1-26.2 defines append-only audit logs and workflow events. Browser screenshots remain deferred to 002EY because this sandbox blocked localhost binding with `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:61:- 002F completed the role-aware shell hardening: `PAGE_PERMISSIONS` and `resolveNavigationAttempt()` now live in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar.tsx` exports the canonical staff nav table for parity tests, and `App.tsx` uses the shared guard helper. Frontend tests assert every non-dashboard staff nav item is gated by the same prototype permission as its page, blocked navigation returns to Dashboard with `blockedPage`, `tracer.lifecycle.run` maps only to `run_tracer`, and unknown/empty-role current-user responses stay neutral. The 002EY `auth-negative` Playwright spec was extended for zero-permission, tracer-only, and invalid stored-session restore checks; local browser execution remained blocked by sandbox localhost `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:67:- For 002G: build admin user/role management on the existing identity catalogue and `/auth/me/` serialization shape. Use `manage_users` as the explicit permission gate, standard envelopes/pagination, session-bound auth, existing `AuditLog`, and frontend navigation/page guard tests through the 002F shared navigation contract. Do not create free-text roles, teams, or permissions; bind only existing catalogue rows. Suspending a user must revoke active sessions; last-system-admin lock-out should be recorded in `ASSUMPTIONS.md` if source-doc-silent.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:69:- 002F2 completed the shallow Sidebar visibility corrective slice: `visibleStaffNavItems()` now lives in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar` consumes it with `allNavItems`, and vitest covers the actual visibility path plus direct route guard behavior for every protected item, zero-permission backend sessions, unknown/empty-role backend sessions, and tracer-only sessions. `tracer.lifecycle.run` still maps only to `run_tracer` and unlocks only Dashboard + Tracer.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:71:- 002G completed admin user-management shell: backend routes under `/api/v1/admin/users/` list/detail users with the `/auth/me/` `roles[{role_code, role_name}]` and `teams[{team_code, team_name}]` shape, bind only existing active `Role`/`Team` rows, set status to `active`/`suspended`, audit role/team/status changes, and revoke active sessions when a user is suspended. Backend gate requires a session-bound active access token plus at least one canonical user-admin permission (`users.user.create`, `users.user.update`, `users.user.disable`); frontend maps those to prototype `manage_users` and adds `admin-users` to `allNavItems`, `PAGE_PERMISSIONS`, and the app route guard. A-014 records the source-silent last active `system_admin` guard: role/status changes that would leave zero active `system_admin` users return `400 VALIDATION_ERROR`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:72:- For 002H: keep the workflow guard foundation domain-neutral. A shared backend transition guard may define from-state, to-state, required permission, action code, and audit/workflow-event metadata, but must not encode loan eligibility, sanction authority, money amounts, or document-completeness rules. Migrate only the existing tracer transition proof to the shared guard and preserve its public endpoint behavior and `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION` / `403 PERMISSION_DENIED` envelopes.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:73:- For 002I: build only a domain-neutral object-level permission helper/test harness. It should accept explicit actor permissions/team codes plus object owner/team facts, allow owner or matching team access, deny missing module permission as `PERMISSION_DENIED`, deny mismatched or unknown object scope as object access denied, and avoid adding public endpoints or querying future loan/member/application tables.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:74:- 002H completed the shared workflow guard foundation. `sfpcl_credit/workflows/guard.py` defines domain-neutral transition definitions/results plus typed errors for unknown action, missing permission, and invalid state. Tracer services now pass explicit actor permission codes into the shared guard for lifecycle actions while preserving existing tracer URLs, success payloads, `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`, audit logs, and workflow events. No schema change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:76:- 002G2 completed the action-aware admin permission gate. `admin_views._authenticated_admin` now takes per-action required permission code sets from `admin_users`: list/detail read needs `users.user.read` OR any write user-admin permission (read fallback per A-015 because seeded `system_admin` lacks `users.user.read`); role assignment and team add/remove need `users.user.update`; suspend needs `users.user.disable`; restore-to-active needs `users.user.update`. `set_status` authorises after parsing the target status (`status_permission_codes`) so suspend and restore are gated differently; check order is `401`→`403`→`400`/`404`, and forbidden partial-permission writes create no `AuditLog` and revoke no session. The now-unused `has_manage_users_permission` helper was removed (`MANAGE_USERS_PERMISSION_CODES` is retained as the read fallback + frontend `manage_users` mapping set). Regression tests cover create-only, update-only, disable-only, and read-only partial roles plus the negative audit/session side effects. No schema change; frontend nav/route unchanged.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:77:- 002I completed the object-level permission test harness. `sfpcl_credit.identity.modules.object_permissions.evaluate_object_access(...)` is a pure domain-neutral helper that accepts only explicit actor facts (`actor_user_id`, `actor_team_codes`, `actor_permission_codes`) and object facts (`required_permission`, `object_owner_user_id`, `object_team_code`, optional `allow_global`). It returns `ObjectAccessResult(allowed, reason, error_code, required_permission, approval_required)`; missing module permission returns `missing_permission` / `PERMISSION_DENIED`; owner and team matches allow; mismatched or unknown scope returns `owner_mismatch`, `team_mismatch`, or `scope_unknown` with `OBJECT_ACCESS_DENIED`; `scope_unknown` sets `approval_required=True`; explicit `allow_global=True` permits unknown scope only after the required canonical permission is present. Tests verify use with `auth_service.effective_permission_codes(user)`, `User.team_codes()`, and `auth_service.team_payload(user)`. No endpoint, schema change, domain model query, audit row, or frontend change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:78:- 002J completed the test-only API contract assertion harness. `sfpcl_credit/tests/api_contracts.py` provides assertions for success envelopes, error envelopes, top-level list pagination, and §44 target `available_actions` item shape. Regression tests cover `/auth/me/` success, admin users pagination, `401 AUTH_REQUIRED`, revoked-session `401 INVALID_TOKEN`, no-permission `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, create-only partial-admin update denial `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, and tracer `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`. No public endpoint, schema change, production import, or frontend change. A-016 records that current `/auth/me/` still returns flat permission-code strings for `available_actions`; the object item shape is asserted only against an internal target-contract sample for future detail endpoints.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:79:- 002K completed the guarded local/dev demo staff seed. `seed_demo_users` refuses unless `SFPCL_DEBUG=true` and `SFPCL_ALLOW_DEMO_SEED=true`, calls `seed_catalogue()`, and idempotently creates/updates only `demo.*@sfpcl.example` users: system admin (`system_admin`/IT), credit manager (`credit_manager`/Credit Assessment), compliance (`compliance_team_member`/Compliance), treasury (`senior_manager_finance`/Treasury), internal auditor (`internal_auditor`/Audit), tracer-only, and zero-permission (`management_viewer`, no team, no permissions). Demo users authenticate through real `/auth/login/` + `/auth/me`; tests cover guard refusal, idempotency, no `e2e.*` changes, active memberships, system-admin user-admin permissions without `manage_users`, tracer-only exact permissions, zero-permission neutral payload, auth login/logout audit rows, admin update `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, and 002J success/error/pagination contracts. No schema, frontend, auth bypass, or broad permission alias change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:84:- Architecture review is due after 002K by cadence (`slices_completed_since_architecture_review` reaches 4). 003A has already been sharpened to add only a protected paginated `GET /api/v1/audit-logs/` over the existing `identity.AuditLog` model, using `audit.audit_log.read` as the narrowest existing audit-read permission. 003B has been sharpened to reconcile the pre-existing tracer-owned `workflow_events` table before creating/owning any canonical workflow-event foundation.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:87:- Endpoints implemented under `/api/v1/tracer/`: create member, create application, sanction, create account, disburse, post repayment, close.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:88:- Minimal statuses only: member `active`; application `draft -> sanctioned`; account `pending_disbursement -> active -> closed`; repayment `posted`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:89:- Guardrails tested: positive amounts only; invalid state transitions return `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`; missing bearer auth returns `401 AUTH_REQUIRED`; revoked access sessions return `401 INVALID_TOKEN`; authenticated users without `tracer.lifecycle.run` return `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`; zero-permission/unmapped frontend roles do not map tracer permissions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:93:- Permission naming convention: §11 (verbs in §11.1); full permission catalogue by module: §12.1–12.13 (auth/user-admin, members, KYC, applications, credit assessment, approvals, documentation, security, SAP/finance, monitoring/default, closure, compliance, reports/audit/config).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:94:- Standard role catalogue: §13.1. Internal roles (§4.1): Field Officer, Deputy Manager–Finance, Credit Manager, Compliance Team Member, Company Secretary, Senior Manager–Finance, Chief Financial Controller (CFC), CFO, Director, Accounts Head, Sales Team User, IT Head, Internal Auditor, System Administrator. External/future (§4.2): Borrower/Member (portal), Nominee, Bank User (not MVP), Subsidiary User, External Auditor.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:104:- Data model tables: §10.1–10.8 (`users`, `roles`, `permissions`, `role_permissions`, `teams`, `user_team_memberships`, `user_sessions`, `sensitive_access_logs`).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:110:- `docs/source/technical-architecture.md` §13.1 says Django views should not contain complex workflow orchestration; multi-entity operations, permissions, calculations, and audit logs belong in explicit service classes/functions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:112:- Keep endpoint URLs and auth behavior unchanged: PyJWT HS256, token lifetimes, JWT claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, and auth audit events.
